# TDD Workflow (Mandatory for All Code Changes)

All agents **MUST** follow TDD for bug fixes, new features, and refactoring. Full plan: `UNIT_TESTING_PLAN.md`. Standards: `TESTING.md`.

## Bug Fix Protocol

```
1. Write a FAILING test that reproduces the bug
2. Verify the test fails before touching production code
3. Implement the fix
4. Verify the test passes
5. Commit test + fix together in the same PR
```

```swift
/// Regression test: Download button shows after book is returned
func testBookReturn_UpdatesButtonState() {
  let mockRegistry = TPPBookRegistryMock()
  let book = TPPBookMocker.mockBook(distributorType: .EpubZip)
  mockRegistry.addBook(book, state: .downloadSuccessful)
  let viewModel = MyBooksViewModel(registry: mockRegistry)

  viewModel.returnBook(book)

  XCTAssertFalse(viewModel.downloadedBooks.contains { $0.identifier == book.identifier })
}
```

## New Feature Protocol

```
1. Write tests defining expected behavior (happy path + edge cases + errors)
2. Implement feature to make tests pass
3. Refactor while keeping tests green
4. Commit tests + feature together
```

## Server Contract Check (Required Before Implementing Server-Defined Values)

Before writing any code that parses a server-provided value — `rel` strings,
URL formats, field names, template syntax — you MUST verify the actual server
response first. Do not assume; read the contract.

```
- [ ] Check the Notion/spec page for the endpoint or document format
- [ ] If available, fetch the real response from the target server (e.g. Icarus)
      and inspect it in the debugger or console logs
- [ ] Build the test fixture JSON from the real server response, not from assumptions
- [ ] If the spec is missing or ambiguous, ask the team before implementing
```

**Why this matters:** Server-defined values are contracts, not guesses. A wrong
`rel` string (e.g. `"sign-out"` instead of `"logout"`) silently passes all tests
when the fixture is built from the same wrong assumption. The implementation
appears to work locally because local credential clearing still succeeds — the
missing server-side session invalidation is only visible to the user at next login.

**How to inspect:** The Xcode console logs every auth entry's raw links at parse
time (`Authentication[<type>] links: [...]`). Launch the app against the target
library and check the console before writing any parsing code.

## Agent Pre-Commit Checklist

- [ ] New/modified code has corresponding tests
- [ ] Tests use real production classes (mocks for DI only, never as the subject)
- [ ] No network calls in unit tests
- [ ] Tests are deterministic (no random data, no real dates)
- [ ] Naming: `test[Unit]_[Scenario]_[ExpectedBehavior]`

## Flaky Test Policy

Immediately quarantine with `XCTSkip("Flaky")`, create a ticket, fix or delete within 1 sprint. Never ignore flaky tests.
